Things I do to break the cycle of fear-based reaction vs observation+choice: https://t.co/XukVs0ttIn

This is what I do to help myself:
•  Take my time, always. I want to make decisions based on observation, not _react_.
•  Practice saying “I’ll have to think about that.”
•  For text comms, don’t reply for at least 15 minutes after reading (I’m very bad at this so far).

This is much worse if someone asks me something. Now it is a need someone has, and I feel obligated to respond immediately. I want to because I always want to help people, but also because that’s how I get validation. So, the stakes are way higher, and that fear response spikes.

I think I get frustrated because to feel safe, I am trained to be ultra-prepared, and to always react to a “problem” ASAP. Any uncertainties delay my understanding and my dysphoric fear response kicks in.
So now I feel (because of me, not the other person) like I have to do a bunch of work to know wtf is going on. I could work through this, and I should, but my automatic reaction is frustration.

So when people something like “have you seen Limitless? That’s the one where he becomes limitless.” 😵‍💫
•  The one? Of what? Is it a show? A painting?
•  He? Who is that?

For me, what I call something is _super_ important to avoid getting confused. Specific, unique names/terms help me remember what they are and what they do. I associate a bunch of info with that name. I get extremely frustrated when variable names aren’t consistent.

Same here. I am extremely pedantic and actually get frustrated when people aren’t specific in their verbiage. I think programming as my job has increased that significantly, and made my reactions to it more intense. https://t.co/6UpJIE85EB

But anyway, I had a point here:
despite my love of learning and teaching, I think I am finally learning that no amount of knowledge, preparation, worry, excitement, or anxiety, will ever bring me peace.
But it was a joyful period for learning. And it has given me relative financial, the foundation built there, learning to write HTML and make very 1995 backgrounds with Kai’s Power Tools.

I’m real hard wired for that. Too well. Highly optimized. Constantly focused on preparing for imagined future that will never be real. A fantasy, pleasant or not.
Humans crave information. Our nervous system uses it to defend itself. It adapts to the environment it senses around us.

My life has always been about subcultures. Being a variation from the norm means you see it in others faster. You can relate in a way that most can’t. Trying to figure out what it is that ties us all together, if we seem to end up in such a different places.

I feel every day how reducing inflammation with meds, supplements, stretching, and standing/moving a bit, reduces my anxiety and executive dysfunction.

Anyway, my brain is not some independent entity from the rest of my body. There are different parts, but they all work together as a functioning system. Treating them as independent systems is something done to make it easier for people to understand.

Now I have pulled the curtain and I see better what’s actually going on. And I am working extremely hard, every moment of every day, to keep going, be present, and choose action — or inaction — with intent.
At the same time, I am likely far more _aware_ of what is actually going on inside of me than I had been. I did everything in my power to not think about those things my whole life.

All of that fills and gaps in my understanding of what I feel in my body: pain is more intense and frequent, everything seems to take more energy and effort, and my executive function is an order of magnitude worse than it was in 2020.

There is strong evidence that inflammation plays a significant role in many cognitive disorders, and increasing evidence that it is a major factor in mood disorders (like depression) as well. Ex: https://t.co/uGDdNgt3vI
It is well established that high levels of cortisol, which is released when our autonomic nervous system believes it’s in danger, increases inflammation and suppresses our immune response.
What I do know is that before I hurt my back, I was very highly stressed at work. I believe this put me into a state where I was much more susceptible to injury and illness.
I don’t know the exact cause, and probably without a time machine and a bunch of scientists I will never know.

But, my memory and cognition didn’t get a lot better. With ADHD, I already have lots of cognitive an executive dysfunction problems, but it seems twice as bad now. You can imagine how this affects work.

With some professional help, I was able to get better and get my back better. It is maybe nine months later, and I have very little neck and shoulder pain. I’ve worked very hard at this, and I feel and can measure those results.
When that was finally dying down, my back and shoulder pain returned with a vengeance. Right back where I had been.
This lasted for a few weeks. The “long tail“ of the fever and inflammation would seem better during the day, but at night would start to come back.

Then, one that was maybe getting a little better, I got really sick. 2 PCR tests told me it was not COVID, but I experienced the significant immune response symptoms that are so frequently described. Body aches, fever, everything felt amplified to 10.

Short version is that I injured my shoulder, and it cascaded into severe back and neck pain. It was so painful I could not sit at a desk and use a mouse (right shoulder, right handed). I would say I was constantly between a 5/10 and 8/10 in pain scale.
So I’m going to talk about the significant increase in memory and executive function problems I have had since I hurt my back and then got pretty sick in early 2021.

I am fighting decades of constant worry about what others think of me. So I often have to tell myself “dude, whatever they think, it’s not your problem.” And keep saying it to myself every time I start worrying about that shit.

That means I have to respect myself enough to 🛑 STOP when I need a break. Sometimes that break is five minutes. Sometimes that break is 24 hours or more. And everybody is just going to have to accept that as what I need to do to not be debilitated.

Key is that I have to put my health first. I am doing all of this to be healthier. I need to have a different kind of relationship with work than I have ever in my life. And I want to do things I know I am capable of, to make my life better.

But don’t get it twisted: it’s work. Hard work. And I only started because I had to — otherwise my future was looking pretty bleak.
An idea that resonated with me: The worry and expectation and anxiety I feel over my imagined future will go away one way or another. Choosing to let go of it now gives me a chance to enjoy my life.

@skoop And to expound even further when not asked, I think a very large percentage of people in societies like ours are constantly stuck in this loop of worry and preparation for the future, and it results in constant low-level anxiety.

@skoop 🖤 to expound a little, I think this is the primary survival pattern of most human beings. Our brains work this way for a reason — It has been effective at keeping us alive in our environment. But for some people, the level of anxiety they experience is debilitating in this env.
But I want to be able to control when I am in the state of stillness. I need to, in fact. Because not being able to find that place was killing me.

When I am in that stillness, or what Tolle calls “no mind“, I am aware of being. I allow myself to feel what is happening in me, observe it, and not fear it. Instead, I have a sense of calm and clarity.
The stillness came when my mind, instead of occupying itself constructing possible futures and preparing for them, was made to focus on what I am experiencing right now.

This is really part of the dominating pattern in my life: hyper awareness of the past (reliving uncomfortable or painful situations over and over),  constantly feeding anxiety about the future. I was almost never present. I only had fleeting glimpses of the stillness.

Woke up, body hurt, wondered how I’d feel when my feet hit the floor. Every time I get up I am semi-surprised when I can stand up straight. But I do, day after day. And if I can’t, I just keep moving as best I can.

Tolle says to die before you die, and find there is no death. Something to that.
And my past has been painful. But it continues to hurt me because I have not been ready to let go of it. I think I am becoming… more ready.
Instead of allowing my mind to experience the only reality there is — now — I was constantly thinking about the future and fearing what would come, based on the pain I held onto from the past.

But this wasn’t something that happened because I hurt my back. I hurt my back because my entire nervous system was in a near-constant state of alert. A defensive stance, like a bunker or tank cat. The pattern fed itself, in obsessive thinking about the past and future.

Like how my lower back hurt all. The. Time. How pain drained my energy faster than anything. How my abdomen was almost always tense, and my breathing shallow. You notice your breathing a lot when every movement you make could hurt.

I had to heal my body, but I soon realized that the real cause was unrelenting anxiety. I knew this was the root of my general unhappiness with life, but my injury made me pay very, very close attention to indicators in my body I normally missed.

Body hurts all over, but I am so much better than I was a year ago, when I needed help lying down on my back at the chiropractor. Unchecked, recursive anxiety had turned my body into a twisted, swollen knot. I couldn’t sit at a desk for weeks.

FE dev in JS is a disaster. It continues to emphasize solving issues that were introduced by increasing complexity, instead of:

1. Reducing complexity
2. Making the dev process easier and less brittle

This approach is a failure for devs. It’s time we stop buying into it.

I believe that the complex, confusing toolchains that are currently popular are

1. Detrimental to developers
2. Provide no benefit to users in most cases

Increased complexity has introduced further tech problems, which we attempt to solve by adding more tech.

2/3

I wanted to help, maybe, just a little. Treat him with respect. Ask about him. Show I cared. That someone cared about him.

I hope it helped a little. We don’t get a lot of chances in life to make a difference. Thought I should take this one.

7/7

Anyway. I paid $6 and maybe it helped. It probably wasn’t smart because the dude certainly could have robbed me or whatever if he wanted, but I just didn’t want to wave him off, and I didn’t want to just give him money to go away, and maybe he just uses it on booze or drugs. 6/x
I looked him in the eye, shook his hand, and told him to take care of himself. To do what he needed to, and to keep moving forward.  5/x

I told him I bet the Lafayette Urban Ministry could help him figure out how to get on Medicare, or at least point him in the right direction. I hope that was right. I asked his name; he said it was Randy. 4/x

I asked him if he had a place to stay, and a place to work. He said he was staying with a friend nearby, and he was working some at the Holiday Inn nearby. Just not enough. He was coughing and said he needed his inhaler, but he didn’t have the money right now. 3/x

I asked where he was going to get something to eat.  He said over at the Marathon a couple blocks away. I told him to get in my car with me and we’d drive over and I would buy him something to eat. So he did, and we did. 2/x

Today I did something I probably wouldn’t advise in general.

I came out of East End Grill, where I’d had a drink and dinner by myself to get away for a bit. This guy on the street told me he was homeless and was going to ask me for some money. 1/x
